  title: Preface to the Treatise on the Principles of Music
  author: Seong Hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Music emerges from Heaven and takes refuge in the human heart. It springs from the void and is perfected through nature's own accord. Thus does it move the human spirit, setting blood and pulse in motion, allowing vital essence to flow freely and the mind to find delight.

    Because hearts perceive differently, so too do sounds differ. When joy is felt, sound scatters and disperses. When anger is felt, sound grows harsh and fierce. When sorrow is felt, sound becomes contracted and diminished. When pleasure is felt, sound becomes gracious and measured. To unite these disparate sounds into harmony depends entirely upon how the ruler guides them. In guidance lies the distinction between right and wrong, upon which the rise and fall of custom depends. Thus music's influence upon governance and civilization runs profoundly deep.

    When we speak of the music of the Five Emperors, none surpassed the age of Yao and Shun, yet they entrusted all to Kui's faithful stewardship. When we speak of the music of the Three Kings, none proved more complete than that of the Zhou, yet they committed all to the Duke of Zhou's creation. The methods they employed are fully recorded in the ancient records and the Zhou Rituals. All these precedents placed ritual and music foremost, punishment and penalty second, thereby cultivating civilization. Thus were reaped the effects of harmony spreading through all directions, and the sublime achievement of suspending punishment for forty years. Yet when the world's moral instruction declined, purity grew turbid and simplicity scattered. Rulers came to rely solely upon punishment and penalty, elevating officials of the law while debasing scholars of ritual and music. The music of the ancients vanished utterly, replaced by licentious and frivolous fashions—the obscene modes of Zheng and Wei, spreading into the shamanic practices of Chen and Chu—until the land itself fell into chaos and ruin. Even the keen ear of Chang Hong and Shi Kuang, or the wisdom of季札 and Confucius himself, could not save it.

    When the Han arose, Shu-sun Tong gathered what remained from the ashes, barely preserving ritual forms. Yet in music, he merely preserved the old ways of Qin, fashioning only court ceremonial music without capturing its fundamental principles. Thus Emperor Wen lamented: "We have not yet found time for this." Though Emperor Wu harbored the desire, he lacked worthy assistants. Li Yan-nian composed music for private chambers, yet it became mere sensual entertainment. Jing Fang created a system of sixty pitches, yet fell into forced analogies.

    In every age—from Jin's Xun Xu and Zhang Hua, through Chen and Sui's Zheng Yi and Niu Hong, to Tang's Zu Xiaosun and Song's He Xian and Chen Yang—brilliant minds have appeared to codify music. Yet each knew only one aspect, understood only the periphery, and neglected the root. How could such efforts speak to music's true mystery? Only Cai Yuanding's work truly grasped the fundamental principles of pitch and temperament. Yet it remained mere theory, lacking practical application—like holding a spade without knowing how to till the soil.

    Therefore we see: music does not perfect itself; it is perfected through human effort. Music does not corrupt itself; it is corrupted through human agency. When all praise the music of Xianchi and Shao, it is because that era was peaceful—not through music's virtue. When all condemn "The Jade Tree Behind the Hall" and the "Feathered Garment Dance," it is because their ruler was dissolute—not through music's fault.

    Our Great East has possessed music since the Three Han kingdoms divided. Yet our instruments were incomplete, our sounds deficient, our traditions mixed with the crude practices of foreign peoples. Who could have brought order to this? Not until Goryeo's middle period did the Song emperor send us the instruments of the Grand Ceremonial Music. And now in our dynasty, the Ming has bestowed upon us the treasures of the imperial archives. Through this, the stone chimes, pipes, mouth organs, and stringed instruments have been restored to us.

    Reverently we consider that the great King Sejong, possessed of Heaven-sent sagacity and mastery of musical principles, sought to cleanse us of former corruptions. When giant millet was produced in Haejuand precious stone in Namyang, Heaven itself scattered its harmonizing essence upon the East, granting a mighty ruler the vision to create anew. Thus were standards established through millet, stone chimes fashioned, musical frameworks created, and notations derived—all to perfect the exactness of tempo and rhythm. Yet in those days only Park Yeon served as master of music, and his knowledge grasped but the surface. How could one person suffice for the sovereign's vast purpose? He could merely assist.

    Great King Sejong's successor possessed even profounder mastery of music, composing many songs and ritually presenting refined ceremonies. His works followed the intentions of his predecessor, though sadly he lacked assistants to aid his vision. This is truly lamentable.

    Now our gracious sovereign inherits sage from sage, respectfully preserving what was established, developing what former sages left undeveloped. The time has come to revive ritual and music in an age of great peace.

    The archived records and notations in the Bureau of Music had decayed through long years, and what survived was fragmentary and corrupt with many omissions. Thus we were commanded—with the noble assistance of Yu Cha-kwang and this humble servant—to revise and complete them. We first explained the principles of pitch creation, then the methods of pitch application. Here are recorded without omission the forms and construction of instruments, their proper use, the movements and sequences of dance, all manner of performance detail. The work is titled the Treatise on the Principles of Music.

    This servant humbly considers that the five tones and twelve pitches form the foundation of music. When matter emerges, feeling arises; when feeling arises, sound is born. The five tones are distributed among the five phases; the length and shortness of the pipes produces clarity or turbidity of sound. The twelve pitches are distributed among the twelve months. Tones and pitches harmonize; rising and falling, diminishing and augmenting, their applications are infinite. These principles are embodied in all eight categories of instruments. Song prolongs speech and harmonizes it with pitch. Dance follows the eight winds and establishes their rhythm. All takes its law from Heaven, not from human contrivance.

    When the harmony between Heaven and Earth is grasped, order prevails and its essential form is obtained. Should this harmony be lost, the human heart becomes excessive and tends toward depravity. The two altered modes exhaust authenticity; the four elevated tones corrupt the root. Thus the distinctions between ruler and subject, affair and thing, all fall into chaos.

    Yet altered and elevated tones exist as salt and blandness exist in food—one cannot use only great broth and unfermented wine. When the true tones remain primary and can temper the altered modes without violating the spirit of harmony, all is well.

    Our nation's music comprises three kinds: the refined, the Tang, and the native. Some serves ritual offerings; some is performed at court assemblies and banquets; some is practiced in village communities. All fundamentally employ the seven modes and twelve pitches. Since abilities vary, understanding music presents both ease and difficulty. The skilled in execution may falter in timing; the precise in timing may miss the principle. Though many know one aspect, few comprehend the whole with clarity. Thus profound is music's difficulty.

    When beautiful sound passes the ear, it vanishes, leaving no trace—like a shadow that gathers when the form exists and scatters when it disappears. With notations, one knows the pace. With diagrams, one identifies the instruments. With records, one understands the methods of practice. This is why we, despite our humble limitations, have undertaken this compilation.
